- ANNOUNCEMENT 📣 Yoga Classes in Dharamkot, Dharamshala – Summer 2025 ⛰️

My in-person yoga classes in Dharamkot are back this summer, running from April to June 2025! Potentially even until mid July ( Based on the monsoon ) If you’re planning your time off, international travel, or a work-from-mountain setup, this is your sign to start preparing.

Summers in Dharamshala are the perfect escape from the heat—cool mountain air, lush greenery, and a thriving yoga community. Whether you’re looking to deepen your practice, build a routine, meet inspiring people, or simply take a break, this season has something for you.

✨ Join anytime for a minimum of 5 classes.
📍 Classes will be at Trimurti, so staying nearby makes it easier to attend. I’ve recommended some of my favourite places to stay. 

This is peak tourist season, so be sure to plan your travel, stay, and classes in advance. If you have any questions, feel free to reach out using the contact details ( number or QR code ) in the post. Whatsap : +91 83528 80554 

See you in the mountains!
— Mihir

- Like the wildflowers that bloom across Almaty’s mountains each summer you too will ‘bloom’ in the right environment.

This July, join us for Summer Bloom : a retreat to reconnect with your breath, body, and the rhythms of wild nature.

When: July 20–26, 2025
Where: Mountains near Almaty, Kazakhstan

Here’s what’s waiting for you:
• Mornings of grounding yoga led by Mihir
• Mindfulness + clarity sessions with Aaron
• Walks through alpine meadows, swims in glacier lakes, and quiet moments with majestic horses
• Cozy cabins, wholesome local food, fire circles, and starlit skies
• A day exploring Almaty city’s best spots
• A pause from the noise. A return to your own rhythm.

This retreat was born from our own journey through these mountains and we’d love to share that feeling with you.

Early bird spots open until May 10.
DM us or WhatsApp +91 83528 80554 to save your place.

Come as you are. Leave rooted, rested, and radiant.

#SummerBloom #JogaRetreats #MindfulTravel #JogaFamily

- Find Your Why - 

True story.
Some mornings I don’t want to go.
It’s raining, I’m sleepy, my body’s sore.
But I’ve learned that showing up just once a day, with presence and purpose builds more power than teaching five distracted classes ever could.

I used to say yes to everything. More classes, more travel, more hustle. Now, I say yes to just one thing a day that I can give my full energy to. It’s helped me prevent burnout, reconnect with my students, and feel joy in teaching again.

This is the kind of inner clarity I want to help other teachers build.

My Teacher Education Program @joga_retreats begins June 29th.
If you’re a yoga teacher who wants to go deeper not just with your students, but with your self this is for you.

📩 DM me or tap the link in bio to learn more.

Let’s build the kind of teaching practice that sustains you.

#TrueStory #YogaTeacherLife #ConsciousTeaching #YogaEducation #TeacherTraining #BurnoutRecovery #ModernYogi #OneClassADay #ShowUpFully #MindfulWork #RainyDayReflections

- 📿 PRANAYAMA ≠ Just Breathwork

What if I told you there’s an ancient art of slowing down death… while still living?
That art is Pranayama—the conscious regulation of the breath.
Not “just breathwork.” Not just a relaxation tool.
But a central, transformative practice in classical yoga.

Most people think of yama as “restraint”—but it also means extension.
And ayama means unconfined, unrestricted.
So pranayama can mean both discipline of the breath, and liberation through breath.
A paradox. A practice. A path.

In Hindu mythology, Yama is the deity of death—the final restrainer.
So when breath is restrained completely, life ends.
But pranayama teaches us to touch that edge,
To sit in the quiet at the bottom of the exhale (rechaka)
And return—not depleted, but expanded.

We prepare with asana to sit in pranayama.
We breathe not to survive, but to transform.

🌀 My pranayama intensive—May We Breathe—is now part of my monthly subscription.
You’ll get lifetime access as long as you stay subscribed, plus over 1200+ other yoga, mobility, and breath classes.

If you’re curious about the depth of breath practice, I’d love to have you join.
💻 Link in bio to subscribe.

#Pranayama #Breathwork #ClassicalYoga #YogaPhilosophy #YogaTeacher #MayWeBreathe #AsanaToPranayama #Rechaka #Yama #Ayama #Prana #VitalForce #Nirvana #ChittaVrittiNirodha #Jogashala

- And. The end of a chapter…
Summer in Himachal always tells a story through flowers, through leaves, and especially through fruit.

These Himalayan raspberries mark the final pages. They show up quietly, golden and wild, just as the air gets heavy and the clouds start rolling in. A last offering from the forest before the next season begins.

I’ve been taking evening walks to forage them slow moments that help me wind down and reconnect with the land. Eating wild and seasonal foods isn’t just about nutrition (though these berries are full of antioxidants and a gentle tonic for the body)… It’s a way of living with the land. Of noticing. Of remembering that nature already knows what we need, when we need it.

A few weeks ago it was rhododendron. Then came the roses for gulkand. Then nettle. And now this. Each fruit, a new verse in summer’s song.

Just a little reminder if you can’t forage where you are, maybe plant something. A berry bush. A herb. Even one pot can ground you in something real.

#WorldEnvironmentDay may have passed, but the message is in the soil. In the hands that harvest. In the joy of eating something you didn’t buy.

#mountainlife #sundays

Namaste 🙏

- Most people think “core” just means abs.
But in yoga it is so much more.

It’s the center that holds you steady when life pulls in every direction.
It’s what connects your breath, your spine, your balance, your organs & even your emotional resilience.

There are so many ways to work with your core:
• Uddiyana Bandha to lift & tone the deep abdominals
• Nauli to massage & mobilize the viscera
• One-legged balances to train reflexive stability
• Backbends to open the front body & strengthen spinal support
• Pelvic floor work / Mula Bandha to activate the root
• Twists to wring out tension & spark internal fire
• Crawling patterns to build functional strength & coordination
• Superman to hollow body rolls for dynamic core conditioning
• Loaded carries to train the core under real-life pressure
• & of course, breath - because breath is the bridge.

In my classes both online & offline we explore all of this.

With breakdowns that help you understand the why behind each movement,
& how to align them with your own unique body & nervous system.

Because the real core work?
It’s not just about looking strong.
It’s about feeling stable; inside & out.

If you feel called join me on the mat let’s go deeper than surface. Click the link in my bio to explore more !

Natural Rubber Mat : @tutti4life

- Some days, your mind races like there are too many tabs open and not enough space to just be.

In moments like that, you don’t need to force silence.
You need something steady to hold onto.
That’s where Box Breathing comes in.

It’s simple. Just 3 minutes of intentional breath and you might feel clearer, calmer, more anchored in your body.

Here’s how:
Inhale – 4 counts
Hold – 4 counts
Exhale – 4 counts
Hold – 4 counts
(Repeat for 3 minutes.)

This is one of the many practices we explore in May We Breathe - a guided Pranayama series at Jogashala.
If your nervous system’s been asking for softness, this space is for you.

✨ Available to all Jogashala members

🔗 Link in bio to join

- Everything we experience is filtered through memory, a reference point in the nervous system, a trace in the mind. In yogic philosophy, this is known as samskara and believed to exist from this life & past lifetimes.
⠀
You only recognize chatter when you’ve tasted silence.
You notice light leak into a dark room. You know loneliness when you’ve felt the presence of a companion.
⠀
& perhaps the most profound realization of all for me is this : Only when you have truly known how to be alone… can you feel connected to everyone & everything.
⠀
This is DUALITY - the fabric of life. It’s not a flaw in the system; it is the system.
⠀
Your moods rise & fall. Just like your breath expands & contracts. Like the clouds in the monsoon sky.
And this very gloomy monsoon sky will dry out again as season changes. 
⠀
One day you feel like the most accomplished version of yourself. The next, like you’re falling apart.
⠀
Yoga doesn’t ask you to fight this. It invites you to observe, accept & meet it with presence. To walk the middle path - not neutral, but aware. This presence, this equanimity becomes your anchor.
⠀
Backbends have always been a mirror for me here.
They ask you to open the front body - the space where we protect everything vulnerable: The heart. The belly. The throat.
⠀
That’s not easy. Especially when we first begin.
There’s resistance. There’s fear. A primal “no” in the body that says “ don’t go there .” 
⠀
But if you stay… if you soften… if you breathe…
something shifts.
⠀
You start to feel instead of force. You sense instead of see. Because unlike other postures, you can’t see yourself in a backbend. You can’t map it with your eyes. You must feel it through sensation. And slowly, over time… the fear transforms into depth.
⠀
Backbends teach you how to dive into the unknown.
To lead with the heart. To feel your way forward - quite literally.
⠀
These are not just postures. They are metaphors for every transition, every moment of change, every time you choose to stay open, even when it’s hard.

We have our entire life ahead but also why not change something NOW ? Because the now can be hard and uncomfortable . But it’s also beautiful. 

And most of all it’s REAL.

latestPosts.caption:
- I find something so humbling about this plant 🙏
 
And Mindful ! 

It teaches us that nature always holds both the trigger and the relief.

That sometimes, what stings us at first… can end up being deeply healing.

Stinging nettle (bichhu booti) is one of those wild, earthy plants that reminds you to slow down and pay attention. You’ll often find her growing quietly on forest trails, usually with dock leaf nearby the very antidote to her sting.

But once you approach her with care hot water, slow cooking, sun-drying - she transforms.

Nettle is packed with minerals: iron, calcium, magnesium, silica. It supports skin, bones, hair, and joints. Great for fatigue, inflammation, and even seasonal allergies.

In Ayurveda, it’s known to have kashaya rasa (astringent taste), and it balances excess Pitta and Kapha. It clears Ama (toxins), stimulates Agni (digestive fire), and strengthens rakta dhatu—our blood tissue. It’s grounding, cooling, and gently detoxifying.

Traditionally used in the hills of Himachal as a leafy green and medicinal tea, nettle holds deep prithvi (earth) energy.

Whether you stir-fry it, blend it into saag, dry it for tea, or try a fizzy forest spritz - nettles are a reminder that true nourishment often comes through patience, presence, and process.

Have you ever been stung by nettle ?

- Same flower, different soil.

It’s hydrangea season and if you’ve ever seen two growing next to each other, one a soft pink and the other a vivid blue, you might assume they’re different varieties altogether.

But they’re not.

It’s the soil that makes the difference.
Acidic soil gives us the blue. Alkaline? That same plant blooms pink.

It’s easy to misjudge and to assume one is more “vibrant,” more “alive,” or even “happier” than the other. But they’re simply expressing what the environment allows them to.

And we humans are not too different.
How often do we project our own perceptions onto others by assuming someone is doing great based on how they look or deciding someone must be struggling just because they seem a bit quiet?

We label. We judge. We scroll past. But rarely do we ask, what soil is this person growing in? What if someone isn’t rude, lazy, or cold… they’re just in survival mode?
Or maybe they’re still healing from something we can’t see.

Being a plant daddy has taught me to ask better questions. 

Not “what’s wrong with this person?” 
But “what’s their soil like these days?”
“What are they growing through?”

If you’ve ever gardened you know that if a plant isn’t blooming, we don’t throw it away we tend to the soil. We adjust the light, the water, the air, the space.

And healing often begins not by fixing the flower, but by nurturing the ground it’s rooted in.

The same is true for people and for ourselves. Small shifts in environment, in support systems and in mindset can change everything.

If you’re a teacher or facilitator and curious about how to work with people and not against their unique terrain our upcoming Yoga Teacher Education helps you do just that. And if you’re seeking your own inner bloom this season, consider joining me in Kazakhstan this July for the Summer Bloom retreat. An invitation to nurture yourself through yoga, coaching, self-study, nature, and rest. ( Both programs are via @joga_retreats ) 

Because whether you bloom blue or pink you’re still a flower. And you’re worth the right soil ❤️🙏

- Mihir
